metadata.name: a working theory #65
metadata.description:
Initial conditions are stated, and then the particles set in motion - the root of generative art. My goal with this piece was to create an illustration that seemed to be from an earlier (or perhaps later?) time; not, at any rate, our current moment. The background is a very subtle gradient; then it is heavily stippled, and followed with a particle system to create more subtle texture. (Look for the very small "hairs" in the background; they are more obvious on the dark ones. They are a subset of the main particle system.) 

Following that, the main particle system is run in real time; I like to "show my work" for generative pieces, as any collector of my previous mints knows, and this is no exception. "Run" your mint for an animated drawing experience. Note that fxpreview() hits a few frames before the end of the full run. I did it this way to ensure a consistent preview. As a result, the preview and the final image will be slightly different, only because the final image has a slightly longer lifespan. 

There are multiple "special" modes, each with a 10% likelihood: 

"spiral" will rotate the canvas as the particle system is running.
"chaos" uses random X/Y vectors during the acceleration phase, rather than X or Y.
"occasionals" adds random large particles in an opposing color.

In addition, there are three possible shapes:

"circle" draws circles for the particles.
"square" draws squares for the particles.
"jagged" draws mostly circles, with a 0.01% chance of a square at a 45 degree angle. 

Finally, there is a non-attribute feature, where the entire piece is drawn at a 45 degree angle. This has a 20% likelihood, but is only apparent on pieces that have no special, or the "occasional" special. Working the math out, you have a 16% likelihood for getting a piece at a noticeable 45 degree angle. 

All main colors have an equal likelihood, but the light background is only 20%.

To see the artwork in full size,  It's highly recommended to open it in live mode.

metadata.name: Flowingcles #91
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

metadata.name: Pepe's Family [V2] #45
metadata.description:
Once again, Pepes are here! This time, you can see them in new styles. Would you like to adopt them? Honestly, they don't seem alone but they are. They want someone to be friend with. You may be a good friend for them. It's necessary to warn you again! Some of them are not really social. So, watch your behavior. Actually, it depends on your chance. You may find an easy going one to adopt. Yet if not, don't worry! They get used to you gradually.

There are 7 traits (48 layers):
Background: 7 layers
Body: 7 layers
Mouth: 8 layers
Eyes & Eyewear: 7 layers
Accessories: 10 layers
Necklace: 5 layers
Fly: 4 layers
